EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS (EDA): A COMPREHENSIVE GUIDE FOR BEGINNER¶

TABLE OF CONTENT:¶

4. INTRODUCE AUTO-EDA APPROACH: PROFILLING

1.INTRODUCTION:

¶

EDA is the most important part of DS/DA Journey. Its usually takes aroung 70%-80% of time in any DS project cycle.

Exploratory data analysis(EDA) is used to explain how the data is, what is the relationship between the attributes, and furthermore.

EDA is not only about dealing with numbers but also understanding meaning relationships between attributes in the data.

An EDA helps us draw conclusions on how the data attributes are distributed.

Before going on to modeling an EDA should be done to understand the data and prepare for the modeling.

EDA is not just about numbers it is also a visual analysis of the data attributes using various graphs suited for each purpose.

A meaningful EDA must help in identifying patterns in the dataset.

2. EDA PROCESS:

¶

Our data contain a lot of missing data. The most common approach to deal with missing data is to drop all the null variable. Another approach is to replace the missing data with mean or median of the column's value for numeric data.In our case, missing data is string data, we couldn't apply the second approach.

b) Univariate Data Visualizations:¶

VISUALIZING UNIVARIATE CONTINUOUS DATA :¶

Univariate data visualization plots help us comprehend the enumerative properties as well as a descriptive summary of the particular data variable.

These plots help in understanding the location/position of observations in the data variable, its distribution, and dispersion

Histogram: ¶

A histogram displays the shape and spread of continuous sample data. It also helps us understand the skewness and kurtosis of the distribution of the data.

In [26]:
#Plotting histogram using the matplotlib plt.hist() function :
plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
plt.hist(df['price'],bins=20)
plt.title( 'Histogram: Price')
plt.show()
In [27]:
# The seaborn function sns.distplot() can also be used to plot a histogram.
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize': (7,7)})
sns.displot(df['price'],kde= False, color='blue', bins=20)
plt.title( 'Histogram: Price')
plt.show()

Density Plot: ¶

A density plot is like a smoother version of a histogram.

Generally, the kernel density estimate is used in density plots to show the probability density function of the variable.

In [28]:
plt.figure( figsize = (7,7))

plt.show()

Out[30]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='odometer', ylabel='price'>

One of the interesting features in seaborn is the hue parameter.

In seaborn, the hue parameter determines which column in the data frame should be used for color encoding. This helps to differentiate between the data values according to the categories they belong to.

The hue parameter takes the grouping variable as its input using which it will produce points with different colors.

The variable passed onto hue can be either categorical or numeric, although color mapping will behave differently in the latter case.

Swam Plot: ¶

The swam plot is similar to a scatter plot. It is often used along with other kinds of plots for better analysis. It is used to visualize the distribution of data points of the variable.

Box Plot: ¶

A box-plot is a very useful and standardized way of displaying the distribution of data based on a five-number summary (minimum, first quartile, second quartile(median), third quartile, maximum). It helps in understanding these parameters of the distribution of data and is extremely helpful in detecting outliers.

3.8. Bivariate Analysis: ¶

The purpose of bivariate analysis is to understand the relationship between two variables

There are three common ways to perform bivariate analysis:

  • Scatterplots

  • Correlation Coefficients

  • Simple Linear RegressionI

We did pratice the scatter plot between two variable in the Univariate Analysis section. Next part is how to analyze corellaction Coefficients between two varibles.

Correlation Coefficient: ¶

A Pearson Correlation Coefficient is a way to quantify the linear relationship between two variables.

We can use the corr() function in pandas to create a correlation matrix:

In [40]:
corr = df.corr()
corr
Out[40]:
price odometer
price 1.000000 -0.634358
odometer -0.634358 1.000000

The below code shows how we can visualize the correlation between features in a matrix form:

In [41]:
sns.heatmap(corr,
            xticklabels= corr.columns.values,
            yticklabels= corr.columns.values,
            annot= True)
Out[41]:
<AxesSubplot:>

The correlation coefficient turns out to be -0.631. This indicates a strong negative correlation between Price and Odometer.

Pair Plot: ¶

Instead of plotting to scatter plots individually, we can also plot a pair plot.

Itll plot a scatter plot for every feature with every other feature.

In [42]:
sns.pairplot(df, diag_kind = 'kde')
plt.show()

Simple Linear Regression: ¶

Simple linear regression is a statistical method we can use to quantify the relationship between two variables.

We can use the OLS() function from the statsmodels package to quickly fit a simple linear regression model for price and odometer:

In [43]:
import statsmodels.api as sm

#define dependent variable:
y=df['price']

#define independent variable:
x= df['odometer']

# add constant to predictor variables:
x= sm.add_constant(x)

#fit linear regression model:
model= sm.OLS(y,x).fit()

#view model summary:
print(model.summary())

The fitted regression equation turns out to be:

Price = 11030 - 0.0436*(odometer)

This tells us that each additional odometer is associated with an average decrease of $0.0436 in used_car's price.

4.INTRODUCE AUTO-EDA:PROFILING

¶

EDA can be automated using a Python library called Pandas Profiling. It is a great tool to create reports in the interactive HTML format which is quite easy to understand and analyze data.

Lets explore Pandas Profiling to do EDA in a very short time and with just a single line code.

Python provides certain open-source modules that can automate the whole process of EDA and save a lot of time. Some of which I have used and are very resourceful are listed below:

  • Pandas Profiling

  • Sweetviz

  • Autoviz

In the context of this notebook, I only introduce the first method: pandas profiling. I wrote another notebook to introduce ohter auto-EDA method here: https://www.kaggle.com/code/ankumagawa/automatic-eda-with-dataprep-autoviz-profiling

For further research, please take a look to my notebook.
